whelkpeopleofdoom<//user_name>
< Time>

<Rate>5</Rate><Text>First of all, @Andrew, this is a freaking GYM, not a sports bar. If you come to the gym to watch TV, then you're doing something wrong. Not to mention there are little TVs attached to every treadmill, bike and elliptical on the second floor with a wide array of channels. Reported.

@Brenden, do not post a review of a place you haven't been to because of something someone else told you. That's unfair and biased. Why don't you just ask her to write a review? Reported.

Okay, onto my actual review...

I saw the legitimate negative reviews, and from what it looks like, management took notice and did something about the cleanliness issues. In my six months here, I haven't noticed any mold in the pool area or the locker room. Overall the place is pretty clean.

The staff is friendly. In my experience they've been patient and helpful.

There are many options here for a good workout. A small-ish (3 lane) pool, an entire floor of cardio machines, tons of free weights, an entire room of spin bikes, a basketball court, plenty of resistance machines... if you're looking to change up your work out every day of the week, you could definitely do so here.

I pay $50/month for my membership that includes a free guest pass every time I come in, which I think is pretty reasonable! And they include a free session with a personal trainer, but that's pretty standard it seems. I've paid a lot more for a lot less at other gyms.

This is the best gym I've ever joined, hands-down. I like it here, and if you're looking for a a gym to join, I highly recommend their free trial, which is what sold me.< /Text>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

< Review>
If you have to rent a storage unit and currently canvassing google looking for the best place/price/value... you can stop right now!  Your "stuff" will find a nice "home" here!    I've rented several units over my lifetime... and for the most part... way too long... but that's comedic tragedy!  : )    This location (18 Hughes) is very clean... it's surrounded mostly by businesses... very quiet... seems very safe... never had an issue in  nearly 10 years!    And of course... like any other place... prices will go up every year.    Now... what makes this place  an excellent experience... is the General Manager... Ghizala! < review>
it's a storage place in a nondescript area of Irvine,  industrial tech area and not located near any junkie encampments. this was my basis for choosing this location. for me this was needed as emergency evacuation of personal belongings from a residence due to a multitude of toxic contaminations occurring at once.

pro tip: if you can, wait for a sale. got lucky in that regard as the 50% off for the unit because of a labor day promotion was a very welcome discount.

the woman behind the counter, Ghizala was courteous and made the process quick and easy.</review>

< Review>
I am very glad I chose to get my storage unit at this location. They had the very best customer service any customer could ask for when interacting with ANY type of business! & this was all because of the kindness and enthusiasm that the Property Manager Ghizala showed to me when I made my reservation!!
Not only did he suggest the right size unit for me, but she also called about 15min before closing when she saw I didn't show up yet to get my unit, just to make sure I didnt lose track of time (which n fact I did!!) I pleaded for her to wait for me to get there.before.closing or else id have no where to put my belongings since it was my last day at my apartment.. Not only did she patiently wait for me to arrive when I was 5min late after closing, but she didn't make me feel rushed in any way and still made sure we walk to see my unit 2 see if was big enough & made sure I could do the gate code properly! It was extremely refreshing to deal with someone that truly loves their job and gives 100% even after closing time!! Thanks Ghizala!<//Review>

<pictures>None</pictures>< Rate>
4<//Rate>
<date>1433269380802</date><Review>I'll gladly pay you Tuesday, for a $.75 Jerry's taco today.

Huh?  Today's Tuesday?!?  SONOFA!!!!!!!!!

Jerry!  Jerry!  Jerry!  Jerry!  Taco!  Taco!  Taco!  Taco!

Yes, you heard right.  Taco Tuesday gets you one of Jerry's street tacos (asada, pastor, chorizo, pollo & carnitas) for the bargain basement price of $.75.  Unfortunately, cabeza, lengua, tripas & potato aren't included & are at regular price.  On the bright side, regular price is just $1.50.  And, to stick it to the other taco shops (I'm looking at you, Rubio's), Taco Tuesday at Jerry's is all day!  Tacos for breakfast, tacos for lunch, tacos for dinner.  It's your call.

I went with asada, pastor, chorizo & carnitas.  What a great value!  I can't recall spending a measly $.75 on something better, in recent memory.  The various meat were tender & juicy.  Of the four, my favorite would have to be the pastor.  It just had that great authentic pastor taste which I adore.  The others were good as well, especially the crunch of the carnitas.  Total including tax = $3.24.  Heck yeah!

A typical salsa bar offers up the usual suspects of green & red sauce, onions, limes/lemons, etc.  The pickled carrots were a little soft & lacked the firm crunch which I like.  Only a minor grievance, however.

Browsing the menu, I saw all the Mexican comfort foods covered.  Such as tortas, enchiladas & weekend specific items like menudo & huaraches. My interest was piqued with a carne asada plate that comes with grilled nopales (cactus), which I think I'll have the next time I come by.   As a welcome start to the morning, breakfast burritos are very affordable at $3.99.

Service was good.  The lady working the front was friendly & I didn't wait long before going to town on my taco plate.  A wooden d√©cor consisted of tables & booths, providing ample seating.  A bamboo thatched roof over the booths gave a rustic hacienda feel to the dining area, with Mexican artwork proudly displayed on the walls.  2 flatscreen TV's for diner's viewing pleasure.

Parking is in a private lot at the Grand Central strip mall.  Jerry's Tacos is located on the right of Nonosina Polynesian Dance Studio.

As a wee laddie, I always rooted for Tom over Jerry in the cartoons, but with all day $.75 Taco Tuesdays at Jerry's Tacos & Mexican Restaurant,, I'm firmly behind Jerry.  For only a little scratch, you can get some major grub on.  Go get you some!

Highly recommend!

<Rating>1</Rating>< review>
In general though, I want to point out that my experiences the last 6 years as a tenant in my home have been pretty terrible. I've had to call in innumerable repairs on the property. I can't seem to go 6 months without something going wrong, and the repairs have mostly been completed either as minimally as possible, only addressing the damage from an actual problem or completed poorly. I've been blown off and dismissed by in house technicians, only to have the exact issue I called about continue until an affiliate (outside or real contractor) comes and addresses the issue, backing up my report. I now request that only affiliates come for my maintenance issues. It's been a nightmare. I've had the hot water heater blow, flooding the garage, almost every window in the home and the sliding back door leaking water into the house with the back door causing the living room to nearly flood. They actually sent a plumber! I've had interior and exterior wall damage from those leaks, a broken drain pipe under the house and the upstairs toilet that had the wrong wax ring installed and leaked into the ceiling. All they did was scrape off the Bubbling paint and crumbling stucco and repaint/stucco. Once drywall gets wet, it needs to be replaced. It took about 4 years before they finally replaced the drywall and only because I called them out a second time for lots of bubbling paint and more crumbling stucco. I had a kitchen cabinet for fall off and hit me on the head, the bathtub spigot shot off and hit me in the shin, the shower valve broke and was streaming hot water when it was turned off, not leaking, streaming. The repair guys didn't replace it properly, and it would only do 1/4 turn. I had my own plumber fix it. When I moved in, the shower slider didn't have a good installed for the doors so the slid but also swung. They would fall off into the tub, and my roommate at the time and I had our kids in the house. Extremely unsafe. And don't get me started on the fact that I've had them out 4 times in the 6 years just to treat termites. If it had been treated properly the first time, I wouldn't have had to have 3 more treatments on the home. I now have damage to some of my personal property. They've already replaced a large portion of the fence around the backyard for termite damage and a good section of the fascia. It was so damaged that it left large gaping holes that air blew through. I noticed when it was blowing into my bedroom in winter through the gaps around my bedroom window at the sill. I got pretty sick that winter. I couldn't heat my room enough and my electric bill was huge because it took a few weeks for them to get the jobs completed to seal up my bedroom again. There are even more issues I haven't named. There's also damage from the repairs/ work done. There are still holes from termite spot treatments inside the home, the kitchen sink has a nice scrape/ gouge from the tech who replaced the leaky faucet, there are dents/ scratches inside and out from other techs as well, and personal peppery damage by repairmen. I just hope they don't try to pin those damages on me when I move. I've documented everything I've been through, everything I've fixed myself and all of my personal property damage.
Future renters beware. Invitation Homes may have some wonderful people on the phone, but at the end of the day they don't make the decisions that put renters like myself in these situations. That's management decision making.</review>

DO NOT RENT FROM THIS COMPANY - EVER!
In the heart of the 2020 pandemic of COVID-19, I received a lease extension offer from Invitation Homes to renew my lease, with RENT INCREASES!  I have lived in the same rental home since June 2014.  Every year, without exception, Invitation Homes increased my rent like clockwork.  This year was no exception.

Three months prior to the expiration of my current lease, of which my rent is slightly above that of comparable homes that are in the exact location and size of mine, Oscar Rendon (DRE #02073326), the designated lease coordinator for the Southern California Invitation Homes (DRE #01950023) office, offered to extend my lease for an additional 12 months with a $50/month increase, or for 24 months with the $50/mo increase for the first 12 months and then a $65/mo increase for the next 12 months.

What business owner, landlord, manager, or person of authority would actually have the nerve to increase costs during the current, world-wide pandemic that we are all experiencing?  Oscar Rendon of Invitation Homes is who.

After receiving such an insulting and rather unfeeling email, I responded to Oscar and reminded him of the current world health crisis and economic troubles.  He in turn graciously apologized and offered to extend my lease without an increase, keeping my rent the same as it is now.  After I thought about it for a few days and reviewed my current and future financial condition, I sent Oscar another email requesting a decrease in rent.  I explained my current situation (which there are many, many people throughout the country, as well as the world, that are in a similar situation), and his response was simply that he would not lower the rent whatsoever.  I informed him that this action might force me to move and that I was asking for the landlord's help in an effort for a win-win proposal.  I can afford a little less rent, and the landlord gets to keep a long-term tenant without having to put in additional capital for leasing advertising, cleaning, showing and paying new lease commissions.

Nope!  He simply said, "no" and sent me the tenant move-out form.  As simple as that.  "You don't like it, then move out!".  Invitation Homes only cares about squeezing as much rent out of their tenants as possible and care nothing about the human beings that their tenants are.

Awful.  Greedy.  No Compassion.  Disgusting.</Review>

We even went as far as writing a follow up letter via postal services and sending emailing in Dec 2017 regarding this matter to ensure our lease would not be renewed, with no response from anyone from Invitation Homes. We had to go on Linkedin to contact the founder of the company in order for someone to help us. Not until Jan 2018 were we contacted by a representative from Invitation Homes saying they never received our 60 day notice, one of their agents by the name of Colette said they probably lost it. After talking with an operations manager by the name of David, he informed us that we would need to write a letter explaining our attempts to decline renewing our lease, which we did, he also explained that if we did not want to renew the lease or be put on a month to month contract that we would have to vacate the home as soon as possible and send pictures of the house once it had been cleaned an emptied so the home could be put back on the market. We had this conversation on Jan 4, 2018, we left the home and sent pictures on Jan 8, 2018. We left the house is such good condition, Invitation Homes used the pictures we took and posted them online as a marketing tool to sell the house. Now, we are being told that we can not get out of our lease until March 8, 2018, and we still have to pay rent even though we have vacated and left the home in selling condition. They are also keeping our deposit. It stressful enough buying a home for the first time but to have to pay rent for another home we don‚Äôt live in for two months, even after we followed procedures set in place by invitation homes to turn in a 60day notice letter, and still be screwed over in the process is unacceptable. This company draws you in by making you feel like you a leasing the perfect home until you decided you don‚Äôt want to use their services anymore and they start to lose paperwork and ignore your letters, phone calls, and emails in attempts to contact them.<//review>< gmap_id>

<review>First things first, I would give this company no stars if that was in any way possible. I am a single mother to two children, one of whom is severely disabled and Invitation Homes has only added unneeded stress to my life. When moving in, it was under circumstances where I couldn't afford to pick-and-choose, however I sincerely regret going with this company.

In the following paragraphs, I will document the reasons behind my complete disdain for this company as well as the employees with whom I have had contact:

1)  Before my move-in was even official, there were many problems. To begin with, the walkthrough was on a Wednesday and still incredibly rushed with the realtor insisting on not staying in a room more than two minutes (maybe because the rooms were significantly smaller than advertised). On top of that, I was told that I could not have the key until Friday, so I made a time on Friday to get the key and do an inspection with utility personnel. Come Friday, myself and two utility men are standing outside the house just waiting for the realtor and the key to what was to be my home. To say red flags came up would be an understatement.

2) My family moved in October and after two years, it was my youngest son's senior year of high school. Naturally, we wanted to stay in the home until he graduated. As such, I asked to simply get a six month lease extension so my son could stay and finish school and then we could all move to a different state. After having multiple phone calls, voice messages and e-mails go ignored, I finally talked to the assistant of my portfolio manager. I was told that a six month extension was impossible: it was either a full year lease (with the annual increase) or a month-to-month deal with an additional $500 added to the rent. The company sees tenants only as numbers on a spreadsheet and does not care at all about their actual lives.

3) The most recent incident is what caused me to finally write a review. To start, the company demanded a $250 pet deposit for my German Shepherd, which was no big deal as pet deposits are typically givens; however, unbeknownst to me, they require a $250 deposit PER pet. Fast forward two-and-a-half years, I buy a puppy to be trained as a service dog for my disabled son who has epilepsy with grand mal seizures as well as severe ASD and other conditions. We have the dog, affectionately named Whoopi by my son, for 10 months with no problems. Then, on December 3rd of this year, we have a technician come out to check the garage and he evidently hears two dogs barking outside and reports it to Invitation Homes. Fast forward almost four weeks later, on December 30th, a notice was taped to my door saying that, within three days, I had to either pay $250, get rid of my second dog or quit the lease - if I didn't do any within the three days, I would be sued by the company and forced to pay $600 in legal fees. The complete disrespect of doing this right after Christmas (especially when it could, and should, have been done in the beginning of the month) as well as not even trying to contact me regarding this matter infuriated me. They could have easily called or e-mailed me to ask if I had an additional dog and then informed me of the deposit per pet policy. But, no. Instead, they chose to wait and then out-of-the-blue provide me with a "comply in three days or get sued" notice. Of course, the representative said they wouldn't charge if we could provide certification that it was a service dog, neglecting the fact that it takes at least two years of training for a dog to become a certified service dog. Additionally, my portfolio manager gave me a snippy, passive-aggressive response when I told her I felt disrespected by the means in which they notified me.

To conclude, this company does not care about tenants or families. Ultimately, money is the one thing they care about and they will find new, and upsetting, ways to pry your hard-earned money from you. If you have a choice in the matter, do NOT rent from them.< /review>< pics>

< review>
Sushi House is a local favorite of the people of Alameda. Whenever people think sushi in Alameda, Sushi House is the go to place. That is for good reason. The food here is very good and consistent, however, big surprise it is the sushi that really shines. Every time that I go I almost always end of getting at least 2 of the various special rolls. The portions here are also very sizable. However the prices here can be quite hefty as well as the wait time. I have never come here and not waited for a table and I have never paid less than $50 here.<//review>

<Review>The restaurant was fabulous, the food was large and delicious, and the sake was cold. It loses a star, sadly, because of the service. It could have been where we were sitting, the rush hour of dinner, the restaurant being short-staffed, or any number of reasons. We had a difficult time placing orders, getting utensils and napkins, and even getting glasses for the bottles of sake we ordered. However! While this docks them a star today, I will be returning due to the food and atmosphere, in hopes for better attention from a server, any server. The only good thing about this place is the service. I remember why I haven't been there for over 8 years during my last visit.

1.  The rice to ingredient ratio in my sushi is 2 to 1. The sushi is enormous because they put so much rice in it. All you taste is rice not the other ingredients.

The teriyaki could be saucier but most come for the rolls.  So many to choose from from raw to fried to baked.  I like to pick up but if they say 40 minutes make it more like an hour on the busy nights.  If you make it there before your food is ready keep a diligent eye for your to-go bags because they may forget to call for you.  All in all pretty darn good Japanese food!< /Text>

#Alotoffood. I enjoyed Sushi House! I was hungry and looking for a decent place with a good value. I came to the right place, because I won't go hungry eating here. I ordered a combo, but instantly wished that I went with sushi and rolls. It's a odd habit of mine. I always want some kind of meat and tempura with sushi as my side item. If only there was a way I could not get full on the the combo stuff and make roll for at least one roll. I guess I need to bring more people so we can share. I was so jealous when the table next to me ordered the Raider Roll! You know I represent, but I had way too much food in front of me to support the roll and my favorite team.

The parking situation can get a little crazy since it's on the corner of the shopping plaza, but I'm sure if you get there early for dinner this won't be problem. I was about to park near the front. The location near shoreline is the best part. This is a perfect for a date and affordable enough for the average college student.< /Review>

110661951617374454080</user_id>
<name>Scott</name><time>1612318879538< /time><rating>2<//rating>< Text>
They have not mastered the covid-19 restaurant experience. The outdoor dining is literally painfully cold. I never complain about a place being too cold, but sushi House outdoor dining area is in an ice cavern. They have overhead heaters, but none of them were on. There's a cold wind blowing between a glass shield and the building.

Service is extremely slow. I understand that they are targeting the doordash and take out customers, but the service for both of them are also extremely slow.

Finally, what used to be a spicy tuna roll tonight was a tuna roll with a blob of sriracha sauce on top.part of what makes a spicy tuna roll tasty is that the tuna and Sriracha are mixed and refrigerated. A blob of sriracha makes for a uncomfortably spicy, poorly balanced tuna roll.

My two star review is a downgrade from what used to be a four star review for this restaurant. some restaurants have succeeded with the covid-19 procedures. But sushi House has not.</Text>

< user_id>
110661951617374454080<//user_id>
<Name>Scott<//Name><Date>1612318879538<//Date><rate>2<//rate>< Review>
They have not mastered the covid-19 restaurant experience. The outdoor dining is literally painfully cold. I never complain about a place being too cold, but sushi House outdoor dining area is in an ice cavern. They have overhead heaters, but none of them were on. There's a cold wind blowing between a glass shield and the building.

Service is extremely slow. I understand that they are targeting the doordash and take out customers, but the service for both of them are also extremely slow.

Finally, what used to be a spicy tuna roll tonight was a tuna roll with a blob of sriracha sauce on top.part of what makes a spicy tuna roll tasty is that the tuna and Sriracha are mixed and refrigerated. A blob of sriracha makes for a uncomfortably spicy, poorly balanced tuna roll.

My two star review is a downgrade from what used to be a four star review for this restaurant. some restaurants have succeeded with the covid-19 procedures. But sushi House has not.< /Review>

I'm not a huge fan of sushi.  This place is just ok.  They can get super busy and crowded at dinner.  I assume people go here for the fact that it's eight next to the beach.  My son likes the beach and so we go here occasionally to eat.  The fish meal is probably one of the better choices.  Though I have been here probably like four times and not eaten anything because I've had a few very meh experiences.  The portions are big at least.  I got to katau once and it was not good.  Also had tempura once that was Soo.  The rolls look good but the best values are the meals.  Still we'll go back because my son likes sushi after the beach.< /Text>

< name>
Ron cooking Garlets< /name>
< date>
1538063943354<//date>
<Rate>3</Rate>< Review>
I give Sushi House a solid 3 stars, the sushi rolls were good, but not spectacular. The bento boxes were huge, the over all quality and quantity was definitely a good value for the price. For two people we had sushi rolls, bento boxes and soft drinks all for $77.

The menu is quite large, five pages. One page is nothing but pictures of all the sushi roll with the name listed under neeth. Great idea for anyone new to sushi.

For dinning out midweek, I was very suprized how busy it was. We didn't feel rushed, but the wait staff seemed to be overwhelmed. At one point I think I counted six sushi chef's behind the counter, but three or four wait staff to deal with well over fourty tables in the main dining area. This is most definitely a high volume establishment.

I was disappointed with the fact that they did not have any seared items, Like seared Ahi tuna. Also be prepared to take home left overs.

If you are new eating sushi or have never tried it but have wanted to Sushi House would be a good place to start.< /Review>

I think this place used to be a Coco's or something, and it still feels like it inside. And sometimes they place us at a table where a child seat really gets in the way of everything.  I give this place two stars (**) on my more than two kids friendly meter.  And when it's busy, which is most of the time, no place to put the stroller if you've got one.< /Review>

< response>
None< /response>
< Text>
This place is reasonably close to my office, so I go here for lunch/dinner quite often. We also had a few company outings here. This is not really authentic Japanese restaurant. One of my Korean coworkers told me the place is owned by a Korean. The food is still quite delicious though (approved by one of my visiting Japanese coworker).

My favorite is the Sake Don. It's basically slices of salmon sashimi, tamago on a bed of sushi rice. They also give slices of lemon. Very fresh, very delicious, generous serving. What more can you ask?

As for the rolls, the serve several fusion dishes like baked scallion rolls. It's definitely different, definitely can't be found in Japan, but definitely good. Bring friends so you can share different varieties of rolls, or just bring a date and enjoy a short walk in the beach afterwards (bring layers, it can get pretty cold).<//Text>

<resp>None</resp><Gmap_id>0x808f86a45a3d7401:0x50ee9025dc45fa4b< /Gmap_id><text>I often go to Sushi House because it is close and affordable.  The wait for this restaurant is pretty long and it lasts late into the night.

I usually get the bimbibap salad which is a bed of salad greens tossed with chrysanthemum leaves and roughly chopped raw garlic and topped with sashimi (salmon, tuna, and tako).  They give a sweet and spicy Korean hot sauce so that people can customize the spiciness.  A bowl of rice is also provided to chow down this dish.  This is a delicious and refreshing dish although not always a hit because of the raw garlic and potential less than premium fish.

Everyone always raves about the Lion King Roll, which is pretty good, but not necessarily worth the almost $12 price tag.  The roll is a baked salmon roll with a sweet miso mayo sauce.  Tasty, but if you have tried it once, try something else on their extensive menu.

Also Sushi House is Korean owned and operated, not necessarily important, but if you are looking for authentic Japanese food this might not be that place.<//text></record></dataset><record>

<pictures>None</pictures><userid>104312584940167668870<//userid>< Gmap_id>

< user>
116796911158844589160< /user>
<username>Noelle Ham<//username>< time>
1381021998418<//time>
< rating>
2</rating>
< review>
I wanted to see the hype because it seems like Sushi House is famous, even for those not that familiar to Alameda.

I ordered the 2 item bento box with salmon terriyaki and tempura (1 piece of shrimp and a few veggies). My friends ordered a lion king roll and orange blossom roll, and the other ordered the katsu donburi. The bento box and katsu donburi come with soup and salad.

The sushi came out first. The orange blossom roll wasn't bad, the salmon wrapped around tasted fresh. But overall nothing impressive. The infamous lion king roll was fine. But definitely not rolled very well. Just picking it up it fell apart.

The katsu donburi bowl came out next. I didn't try any of it but my friend seemed unenthusiastic. She was picking around it, and the katsu looked soggy.

After about 20 min my box finally came out. The tempura was cold and bit soggy. The salmon was warm. It seemed like the entire time I was waiting for my box, my food was just sitting there. Meh.

The service was poor. Our waitress seemed rude and every time we asked for anything we'd get an eye roll. We didn't get spoons when she dropped off our soups (we just drank it from the bowl because we were starving) and then when my friend asked for a spoon for her katsu bowl, she handed her a plastic spoon. Seriously? There was a waitress that was going around filling waters and also cashed us out, she seemed nice though!

Do I see the hype? NOPE! There's better sushi places to eat in Alameda.</review>
